{"title_page": "Los Pollos Hermanos", "text_new": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name         = Los Pollos Hermanos \n| image        = File:Los_Pollos_Hermanos_logo.png\n| image_size   = 240px\n| caption      = Logo\n| source       = [[Breaking Bad]] / [[Better Call Saul]]\n| first        = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Breaking Bad''''':\n* \"[[Mandala (Breaking Bad)|Mandala]]\" (2009)\n* '''''Better Call Saul''''':\n* \"[[Witness (Better Call Saul)|Witness]]\" (2017)\n}}\n| last = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Breaking Bad''''':\n* \"Bug\" (2011)\n}}\n| creator      = [[Vince Gilligan]] <br /> [[George Mastras]]\n| genre        = [[Crime drama]]\n| type         = Restaurant\n| located_in   = Albuquerque, New Mexico, United States\n|\n}}\n\n'''Los Pollos Hermanos''' (Spanish for '''The Chicken Brothers''') is a [[fried chicken]] restaurant that originated in the television series ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' and ''[[Better Call Saul]]''. In the fictional universe of ''Breaking Bad'', Los Pollos Hermanos is a [[front organization]] for [[Gustavo Fring]]'s meth manufacturing and distribution operation. The set used for the restaurant in the show was at a [[Twisters]] branch in [[South Valley, New Mexico]].  Due to the shows' popularity, Los Pollos Hermanos has also appeared on numerous occasions and locations a real-life [[pop-up restaurant]].\n\n==In-universe history==\nLos Pollos Hermanos was founded by Chilean nationals [[Gustavo Fring]] and Max Arcienega in Mexico. An apocryphal story as told in a fictional television commercial suggests that it was inspired by recipes cooked by Gus' uncles. Eventually Gustavo Fring emigrated to the United States and opened branches primarily in [[New Mexico]], and the chain grew to have over a dozen locations throughout the [[American Southwest]]. Los Pollos Hermanos trucks were used to smuggle drugs across the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]]. The restaurant eventually became a subsidiary of fictional German shipping conglomerate, Madrigal Electromotive GmbH. After Fring's death at the hands of [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]] and [[Hector Salamanca]], the chain was closed, with the flagship restaurant in Albuquerque reverting to Twisters, the same restaurant which is used as the filming set in real-life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/netflix-el-camino-breaking-bad-movie-references-breakdown-2019-10|title=30 details you may have missed in Netflix's 'Breaking Bad' movie|first=Olivia Singh, Kirsten|last=Acuna|website=Insider}}</ref>\n\n==Real life restaurants==\nIn 2015, ''Breaking Bad'' creator [[Vince Gilligan]] revealed on a Reddit AMA that there were talks at Sony to make Los Pollos Hermanos into a real restaurant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/a-real-life-los-pollos-hermanos-restaurant-is-in-the-works-with-backing-from-breaking-bad-creator-10219360.html|title=A real life Los Pollos Hermanos restaurant is in the works|date=May 1, 2015|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the restaurant's logo was the subject of a lawsuit brought by Humberto Puentes-Segura, the artist who created it, alleging that Sony infringed on his copyright by selling merchandise emblazoned with the image without permission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/breaking-bad-los-pollos-hermanos-artist-sues-sony-942720|title=Artist Behind 'Breaking Bad's' Los Pollos Hermanos Sues Sony|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Los Pollos Hermanos was a [[pop-up restaurant]] that toured several cities. It was announced to open from April 9-10 in [[New York City]] on [[Pearl Street (Manhattan)]], although the pop-up reportedly only offered [[curly fries]] on the menu and not chicken at all.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2017/4/10/15242908/los-pollos-hermanos-breaking-bad-nyc|title=\u2018Breaking Bad\u2019 Pop-Up Restaurant Pretty Much Only Consists of Curly Fries|first=Stefanie|last=Tuder|date=April 10, 2017|website=Eater NY}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4724761/breaking-bad-los-pollos-hermanos-restaurant-nyc/|title=Breaking Bad's Los Pollos Hermanos Restaurant Is Pretty Real|website=Time}}</ref> Los Angeles on April 10-11,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamag.com/digestblog/los-pollos-hermanos-popup-downtown-los-angeles/|title=Los Pollos Hermanos Is Popping Up Downtown on Wednesday and Thursday Los Angeles Magazine|first=Joe|last=Donatelli|date=March 28, 2017}}</ref> and [[Austin, Texas]] for [[South by Southwest]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2017/3/28/15096138/los-pollos-hermanos-breaking-bad-better-call-saul-nyc|title=\u2018Breaking Bad\u2019 Restaurant Los Pollos Hermanos Is Popping Up in NYC|first=Melissa|last=McCart|date=March 28, 2017|website=Eater NY}}</ref> \n\nOn January 20, 2018, to celebrate the 10th anniversary of the beginning of ''Breaking Bad'', the Twisters location used to film the restaurant on the show was temporarily renovated for a single day to look like Los Pollos Hermanos.<ref>https://hellogiggles.com/reviews-coverage/breaking-bad-anniversary-los-pollos-hermanos/</ref> The occasion was paid for by two \"superfans\" Edward Candelaria and Marq Smith, and was allegedly unsanctioned by Sony Pictures or AMC.<ref>https://www.grubstreet.com/2018/01/los-pollos-hermanos-returns-for-breaking-bad-anniversary.html</ref><ref>https://www.foodandwine.com/news/los-pollos-hermanos-pop-up-albuquerque</ref> The event also coinincided with the local filming of [[Better Call Saul (season 4)|''Better Call Saul'' Season 4]].\n\nIn late 2019 the \"Breaking Bad Experience\" pop-up restaurant operated on 7100 [[Santa Monica Boulevard]] in [[West Hollywood, California]], and included items reminiscent of Los Pollos Hermanos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodandwine.com/news/breaking-bad-el-camino-movie-pop-los-angeles|title=A 'Breaking Bad' Pop-Up Is Coming to L.A.|website=Food & Wine}}</ref> A few days later, it was announced that [[delivery kitchen]] network Family Style Inc. partnered with [[Sony Pictures Consumer Products]] and began being offering Los Pollos Hermanos through [[Uber Eats]] in select markets, starting with [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/breaking-bad-restaurant-los-pollos-hermanos-launches-virtual-restaurant-1249063|title='Breaking Bad' Restaurant Los Pollos Hermanos Comes to Life Via Virtual Restaurant|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodandwine.com/news/breaking-bad-los-pollos-hermanos-uber-eats|title=Uber Eats Will Deliver Food from 'Breaking Bad' Restaurant Los Pollos Hermanos|website=Food & Wine}}</ref> A pop-up location in [[Venice Beach, California]] also opened on October 24, 2019 for the premiere of ''[[El Camino: A Breaking Bad Movie]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2019/09/27/breaking-bad-los-pollos-hermanos-pop-up-restaurant-venice-el-camino-movie/|title='Breaking Bad' Movie Brings Los Pollos Hermanos to Real Life|website=TMZ}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bubba Gump Shrimp Company]], restaurant inspired by characters from ''[[Forrest Gump]]''\n* [[Big Kahuna Burger]], a fictional burger chain from ''[[Pulp Fiction]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lphishiring.com Los Pollos Hermanos]\n\n{{Breaking Bad}}\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pollos Hermanos, Los}}\n[[Category:Fictional restaurants]]\n[[Category:Breaking Bad]]\n[[Category:Theme restaurants]]\n[[Category:Fried chicken]]\n[[Category:Fictional elements introduced in 2009]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name         = Los Pollos Hermanos \n| image        = File:Los_Pollos_Hermanos_logo.png\n| image_size   = 240px\n| caption      = Logo\n| source       = [[Breaking Bad]] / [[Better Call Saul]]\n| first        = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Breaking Bad''''':\n* \"[[Mandala (Breaking Bad)|Mandala]]\" (2009)\n* '''''Better Call Saul''''':\n* \"[[Witness (Better Call Saul)|Witness]]\" (2017)\n}}\n| last = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Breaking Bad''''':\n* \"Bug\" (2011)\n}}\n| creator      = [[Vince Gilligan]] <br /> [[George Mastras]]\n| genre        = [[Crime drama]]\n| type         = Restaurant\n| located_in   = Albuquerque, New Mexico, United States\n|\n}}\n\n'''Los Pollos Hermanos''' (Spanish for '''The Chicken Brothers''') is a [[fried chicken]] restaurant that originated in the television series ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' and ''[[Better Call Saul]]''. In the fictional universe of ''Breaking Bad'', Los Pollos Hermanos is a [[front organization]] for [[Gustavo Fring]]'s meth manufacturing and distribution operation. The set used for the restaurant in the show was at a [[Twisters]] branch in [[South Valley, New Mexico]].  Due to the shows' popularity, Los Pollos Hermanos has also appeared on numerous occasions and locations a real-life [[pop-up restaurant]].\n\n==In-universe history==\nLos Pollos Hermanos was founded by Chilean nationals [[Gustavo Fring]] and Max Arcienega in Mexico. An apocryphal story as told in a fictional television commercial suggests that it was inspired by recipes cooked by Gus' uncles. Eventually Gustavo Fring emigrated to the United States and opened branches primarily in [[New Mexico]], and the chain grew to have over a dozen locations throughout the [[American Southwest]]. Los Pollos Hermanos trucks were used to smuggle drugs across the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]]. The restaurant eventually became a subsidiary of fictional German shipping conglomerate, Madrigal Electromotive GmbH. After Fring's death at the hands of [[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walter White]] and [[Hector Salamanca]], the chain was closed, with the flagship restaurant in Albuquerque reverting to Twisters, the same restaurant which is used as the filming set in real-life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insider.com/netflix-el-camino-breaking-bad-movie-references-breakdown-2019-10|title=30 details you may have missed in Netflix's 'Breaking Bad' movie|first=Olivia Singh, Kirsten|last=Acuna|website=Insider}}</ref>\n\n==Real life restaurants==\nIn 2015, ''Breaking Bad'' creator [[Vince Gilligan]] revealed on a Reddit AMA that there were talks at Sony to make Los Pollos Hermanos into a real restaurant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/a-real-life-los-pollos-hermanos-restaurant-is-in-the-works-with-backing-from-breaking-bad-creator-10219360.html|title=A real life Los Pollos Hermanos restaurant is in the works|date=May 1, 2015|website=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the restaurant's logo was the subject of a lawsuit brought by Humberto Puentes-Segura, the artist who created it, alleging that Sony infringed on his copyright by selling merchandise emblazoned with the image without permission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/breaking-bad-los-pollos-hermanos-artist-sues-sony-942720|title=Artist Behind 'Breaking Bad's' Los Pollos Hermanos Sues Sony|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Los Pollos Hermanos was a [[pop-up restaurant]] that toured several cities. It was announced to open from April 9-10 in [[New York City]] on [[Pearl Street (Manhattan)]], although the pop-up reportedly only offered [[curly fries]] on the menu and not chicken at all.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2017/4/10/15242908/los-pollos-hermanos-breaking-bad-nyc|title=\u2018Breaking Bad\u2019 Pop-Up Restaurant Pretty Much Only Consists of Curly Fries|first=Stefanie|last=Tuder|date=April 10, 2017|website=Eater NY}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/4724761/breaking-bad-los-pollos-hermanos-restaurant-nyc/|title=Breaking Bad's Los Pollos Hermanos Restaurant Is Pretty Real|website=Time}}</ref> Los Angeles on April 10-11,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lamag.com/digestblog/los-pollos-hermanos-popup-downtown-los-angeles/|title=Los Pollos Hermanos Is Popping Up Downtown on Wednesday and Thursday Los Angeles Magazine|first=Joe|last=Donatelli|date=March 28, 2017}}</ref> and [[Austin, Texas]] for [[South by Southwest]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ny.eater.com/2017/3/28/15096138/los-pollos-hermanos-breaking-bad-better-call-saul-nyc|title=\u2018Breaking Bad\u2019 Restaurant Los Pollos Hermanos Is Popping Up in NYC|first=Melissa|last=McCart|date=March 28, 2017|website=Eater NY}}</ref> \n\nOn January 20, 2018 to celebrate the 10th anniversary of the beginning of ''Breaking Bad'', the Twisters location used to film the restaurant on the show was temporarily renovated to look like Los Pollos Hermanos.<ref>https://hellogiggles.com/reviews-coverage/breaking-bad-anniversary-los-pollos-hermanos/</ref> The occasion was paid for by two \"superfans\" Edward Candelaria and Marq Smith, and was allegedly unsanctioned by Sony Pictures or AMC.<ref>https://www.grubstreet.com/2018/01/los-pollos-hermanos-returns-for-breaking-bad-anniversary.html</ref><ref>https://www.foodandwine.com/news/los-pollos-hermanos-pop-up-albuquerque</ref> The event also coinincided with the local filming of [[Better Call Saul (season 4)|''Better Call Saul'' Season 4]].\n\nIn late 2019 the \"Breaking Bad Experience\" pop-up restaurant operated on 7100 [[Santa Monica Boulevard]] in [[West Hollywood, California]], and included items reminiscent of Los Pollos Hermanos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foodandwine.com/news/breaking-bad-el-camino-movie-pop-los-angeles|title=A 'Breaking Bad' Pop-Up Is Coming to L.A.|website=Food & Wine}}</ref> A few days later, it was announced that [[delivery kitchen]] network Family Style Inc. partnered with [[Sony Pictures Consumer Products]] and began being offering Los Pollos Hermanos through [[Uber Eats]] in select markets, starting with [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/breaking-bad-restaurant-los-pollos-hermanos-launches-virtual-restaurant-1249063|title='Breaking Bad' Restaurant Los Pollos Hermanos Comes to Life Via Virtual Restaurant|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref><ref>